Wash and dry all produce. Adjust rack to middle position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Strip and mince enough @rosemary{1/4%ounce} leaves to give you 1 TBSP; set aside remaining sprigs. Halve @fingerling potatoes{12%ounce} lengthwise. Toss potatoes with a large drizzle of @olive oil{4%tsp}, 2 tsp minced rosemary, and @salt{} and @pepper{} on a #baking sheet{} and arrange cut-side down.

Roast potatoes in oven until tender and crisped, about ~{25%minutes} (we'll add more to the sheet after ~{15%minutes}). Trim woody bottom ends from @asparagus{8%ounce}. Toss with a drizzle of olive oil in a #medium bowl{} and season with salt and pepper. Pat @New York strip steak{12%ounce} dry with a #paper towel{}.

Once potatoes have roasted 15 minutes, remove baking sheet from oven and add asparagus to same sheet (scoot potatoes over if you need to). Return sheet to oven and continue roasting until asparagus is tender and lightly browned and potatoes are done, about ~{10%minutes} more.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of olive oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Season steak with salt and pepper. Add to pan and cook to desired doneness, ~{3-5%minutes} per side. Remove from pan and set aside on a #plate{} to rest.

Pour out any excess grease in pan used for steak, then return to stove, reducing heat to low. Add @water{1/4%cup} and @chicken stock concentrate{1}, stirring to combine. Stir in 1/2 tsp minced rosemary (use more or less to taste), then add @fig jam{1%ounce}, @balsamic glaze{2%tbsp}, and @butter{2%tbsp}. Stir to melt butter and dissolve jam. Let simmer until thick and glossy, ~{1-2%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

Divide potatoes and asparagus between plates. Pour any resting juices from steak into sauce and stir to combine.

> If sauce seems thick, add a splash of water.

Divide steak between plates, then drizzle with sauce. Garnish with reserved rosemary sprigs for decoration.